# Mocked object injection
If you want to use mocked `Player` in tests you should use `@Mock` and `@InjectMocks`.  
Suggestion to add `@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)` which has built in method call `MockitoAnnotations.initMocks(this);` in `@BeforeEach` method.
```java
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
class GameTest {

  @Mock
  private Player player;

  @InjectMocks
  private Game game;
  
  @Test
  void getPlayer() {
    when(player.getPlayer()).thenReturn(&quot;player1&quot;);
    var gamePlayer = game.getPlayer();
    assertEquals(&quot;player1&quot;, gamePlayer);
  }

}
```
---
# Real object injection
Real object injection has nothing with mockito. Mockito framework is used to mock objects to test unit, not full flow.
**How to use real object - depends on used framework**.  
# Spring
```java
@ExtendWith(SpringExtension.class)
@ContextConfiguration(classes = {Tool.class, Player.class})
class GameTest {

  @Inject
  private Game game;

  @Test
  void getPlayer() {
    var gamePlayer = game.getPlayer();
    assertEquals(&quot;player1&quot;, gamePlayer);
  }

}
```

# Spring-boot
```java
@SpringBootTest
class GameTest {

  @Autowired
  private Game game;

  @Test
  void getPlayer() {
    var gamePlayer = game.getPlayer();
    assertEquals(&quot;player1&quot;, gamePlayer);
  }

}
```

# No framework
```java
class GameTest {

  private Game game;

  @BeforeEach
  void setUp() {
    var tool = new Tool();
    var player = new Player(tool);
    game = new Game(player);
  }

  @Test
  void getPlayer() {
    var gamePlayer = game.getPlayer();
    assertEquals(&quot;player1&quot;, gamePlayer);
  }
}
```

It seems you have tests design issue instead of how to inject your dependencies. The purpose of a unit test is to isolate and test at the best case, one functionality or one class. Here you have to isolate your Game test and test it only.

    @ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
    class GameTest {
    
      @Mock
      private Player player;
    
      @InjectMocks
      private Game game;
      
      @Test
      void testGetPlayer() {
        when(player.getPlayer()).thenReturn(&quot;player&quot;);
        var gamePlayer = game.getPlayer();
        assertEquals(&quot;player&quot;, gamePlayer);
      }
    }

We use `@InjectMocks` for the class `undertest`, so here `Game`. Apply separation of concerns here.

